  "doc_id": "17679",
  "text": "The aim of the present research was to extend our immunological analyses of the FSL model by testing the hypothesis that the FSL rats would exhibit significant declines in antigen-specific immunity compared with FRL control animals. In the first study, rats were immunized with keyhole limpet hemocyanin (KLH), a novel protein antigen that elicits a clonally diverse response involving processing and presentation by monocytes and T-and B-cell cooperation [CITATION_1] . KLH has been used widely in studies documenting changes in specific antibody production during psychological stress [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and after administration of immunomodulatory hormones (29 -32) . In the present study, serum levels of immunoglobulin (Ig)M, IgG, IgG1, and IgG2a were measured after primary immunization with KLH. A second study was conducted examining strain differences in stimulated production of interferon (IFN)-␥, a cytokine that is released by T-helper type 1 (Th1) cells. Th1 cytokines drive production of IgG2a from B cells [CITATION_6] , and we hypothesized that strain differences in the production of IFN-␥ might underlie strain differences in the production of KLHspecific IgG2a, if any.",
